Requirements: Empty repository with a remote on machine M1 with git-flow initialised (`develop` branch is required).

Steps to reproduce:

# M1: create a feature branch;
# M1: check out the feature branch;
# M1: make few commits in the feature branch (N > 1);
# M1: push the feature branch to remote;
# M2: pull the changes and checkout the develop branch;
# M2: merge the feature branch into develop;
# M2: push the merge commit to origin;
# M1: fetch (not pull) the changes from origin;

Now observe, that develop branch on M1 is N commits behind the remote one when it actually should be only 1 commit behind (the 1 commit that is merge between feature and develop branches). The SourceTree counts the commits using the last, not the first parent of the merge commit. To fix this you can use `--first-parent` flag that appeared in git 1.8.4.

Please ignore this improvement request if that's intended behavior.

There is support for linking to JIRA issues in SourceTree. Many thanks.

But I still need the discipline to type the issue reference in every new commit message. Being able to select a previous commit message helps, but it would be nice if we could somehow define that, for the time being, `SRCT-5345` and `SRCT-3534` are the issues that I am working on, and that they are added to the first line of the commit log automatically ... or something.

(We tend to use the format:

{code}
SRCT-5345: added links to the other side

It turned out that we are not alone. In this commit we added links to the other side in a first version. This is rather a POC, than finished. Will be refined in later commits.
{code}

).

If you set your SSH config to only work with non-weak ciphers (see https://stribika.github.io/2015/01/04/secure-secure-shell.html), SourceTree is no longer able to work with remotes.

For example, adding this line in your SSH config:

{code}
    Ciphers chacha20-poly1305@openssh.com,aes256-gcm@openssh.com,aes128-gcm@openssh.com,aes256-ctr,aes192-ctr,aes128-ctr
{code}

Will result in the following error when trying to clone from remote:

{code}
Cloning from git@bitbucket.com:user/repo
/etc/ssh_config line 35: Bad SSH2 cipher spec 'chacha20-poly1305@openssh.com,aes256-gcm@openssh.com,aes128-gcm@openssh.com,aes256-ctr,aes192-ctr,aes128-ctr'.
fatal: Could not read from remote repository.
{code}

The problem persists for non-weak values for other security attributes:

{code}
HostKeyAlgorithms ssh-ed25519-cert-v01@openssh.com,ssh-rsa-cert-v01@openssh.com,ssh-rsa-cert-v00@openssh.com,ssh-ed25519,ssh-rsa
KexAlgorithms curve25519-sha256@libssh.org,diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha256
{code}
